  "text": "We now conclude the presentation of matrix-free approach to geostatistical filter that we propose, and that we summarized in Figure 3 . Starting from a noisy signal observed across ሚ −1/2 ሚ Figure 3 : Matrix-free approach to geostatistical filtering. a spatial domain, we first determine the anisotropy and covariance parameters characterizing each component of the signal. The anisotropy parameters can be determined using for instance gradient based algorithms on a smoothed out version of the signal, or using auxiliary variables. The covariance parameters can be determined using local variogram modeling. This first step is actually common to any geostationary filtering approach aiming at incorporating local information into the process [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Besides, the spatial domain is triangulated at the observed locations. In the particular case of observation on a grid, the triangulation needs no work as we can simply divide the grid cells into triangles or tetrahedrons.",
